Addressing stereotype threat is not optional; it is essential for fairness and innovation. First, educators should normalize mistakes as part of learning, framing errors as stepping stones rather than failures. Second, role models matter—showing diverse scientists in curricula and inviting guest speakers from underrepresented groups signals that success is attainable. Third, mentorship programs help students build confidence and see a clear path forward. Fourth, institutions can reframe assessments to reduce high-stakes pressure; low-stakes quizzes or collaborative projects lower anxiety while still measuring understanding.

